pg 1200w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/5529x3110+0+288/resize/1600/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fac%2F43%2Fd414b1024c058a8bb33902b7271f%2Fgettyimages-963067608.jpg 1600w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/5529x3110+0+288/resize/1800/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fac%2F43%2Fd414b1024c058a8bb33902b7271f%2Fgettyimages-963067608.jpg 1800w" data-template="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/5529x3110+0+288/resize/{width}/quality/{quality}/format/{format}/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fac%2F43%2Fd414b1024c058a8bb33902b7271f%2Fgettyimages-963067608.jpg" sizes="(min-width: 1025px) 650px, calc(100vw - 30px)" class="img" type="image/jpeg" /&gt;             &lt;img src="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/5529x3110+0+288/resize/1100/quality/50/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fac%2F43%2Fd414b1024c058a8bb33902b7271f%2Fgettyimages-963067608.jpg" data-template="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/5529x3110+0+288/resize/{width}/quality/{quality}/format/{format}/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fac%2F43%2Fd414b1024c058a8bb33902b7271f%2Fgettyimages-963067608.jpg" class="img" alt="MIDDLETOWN, CT - MAY 27: Students toss their hats in the air at the conclusion of their commencement ceremony on May 27, 2018 at Wesleyan University in Middletown, Connecticut. Law professor Anita Hill spoke at the ceremony." loading="lazy" /&gt;         &lt;/picture&gt; &lt;/div&gt; &lt;div class="credit-caption"&gt;     &lt;div class="caption-wrap"&gt;         &lt;div class="caption" aria-label="Image caption"&gt;             &lt;p&gt;                 MIDDLETOWN, CT - MAY 27: Students toss their hats in the air at the conclusion of their commencement ceremony on May 27, 2018 at Wesleyan University in Middletown, Connecticut. Law professor Anita Hill spoke at the ceremony. (Photo by Eduardo Munoz Alvarez/Getty Images)                 &lt;b class="credit" aria-label="Image credit"&gt;                                          Eduardo Munoz Alvarez/Getty Images                                      &lt;/b&gt;                 &lt;b class="hide-caption"&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;             &lt;/p&gt;         &lt;/div&gt;               &lt;b class="toggle-caption"&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;     &lt;/div&gt;       &lt;/div&gt;    &lt;/div&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Today, after two decades, graduate students will no longer be able to take out unlimited federal student loans to cover the full cost of their education. The Trump administration is now capping graduate school loans for many students at $20,500 per year and a total of $100,000. Although a federal court has temporarily blocked a small part of this plan, the U.S. Education Department confirmed to NPR that the loan limits will begin on July 1. Republicans used last year's One Big Beautiful Bill Act to eliminate the Grad PLUS program and limit graduate loan amounts. They reasoned that borrowers would opt for cheaper programs, prompting more expensive schools to lower their prices to stay competitive. But is that reasoning sound? Here's &lt;a href="https://www.npr.org/2026/06/28/nx-s1-5805988/cost-education-student-loan-tuition-graduate-school" target="_blank"&gt;what the research shows&lt;/a&gt;:&lt;br&gt;&lt;/p&gt;   &lt;ul class="edTag"&gt;&lt;li&gt;🎓 For every additional dollar that students received in loans, graduate schools raised their prices by $0.64 after accounting for the grants they provided, according to a team of researchers who studied the Grad PLUS program.&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;🎓 Jeff Denning, an economist whose research found the clearest connection between federal loans and college prices, says that predicting student behavior can be challenging. A significant reduction in federal loans might lead students to opt for less expensive programs, but it could also drive them to seek out private loans.&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;🎓 There is strong evidence that reducing access to financial aid can prompt students to stop enrolling in programs, says Dominique Baker, an associate professor of education and public policy at the University of Delaware. This is especially evident among lower-income students, who often lack sufficient credit history to qualify for private student loans.&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;🎓 Recent analyses suggest these new limits will affect roughly 30% of graduate borrowers.&lt;/li&gt;&lt;/ul&gt;   &lt;h3 class="edTag"&gt;Life advice&lt;/h3&gt;   &lt;div id="resg-s1-130454" class="bucketwrap image large"&gt;             &lt;div     class="imagewrap has-source-dimensions"     data-crop-type=""     style="         --source-width: 5568;         --source-height: 3132;     " &gt;         &lt;picture&gt;             &lt;source srcset="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/5568x3132+0+290/resize/400/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F04%2F09%2F0cc743054c958358ca31a45e2fd8%2Fgettyimages-2159963732.jpg 400w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/5568x3132+0+290/resize/600/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F04%2F09%2F0cc743054c958358ca31a45e2fd8%2Fgettyimages-2159963732.jpg 600w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/5568x3132+0+290/resize/800/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F04%2F09%2F0cc743054c958358ca31a45e2fd8%2Fgettyimages-2159963732.jpg 800w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/5568x3132+0+290/resize/900/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F04%2F09%2F0cc743054c958358ca31a45e2fd8%2Fgettyimages-2159963732.jpg 900w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/5568x3132+0+290/resize/1200/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F04%2F09%2F0cc743054c958358ca31a45e2fd8%2Fgettyimages-2159963732.jpg 1200w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/5568x3132+0+290/resize/1600/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F04%2F09%2F0cc743054c958358ca31a45e2fd8%2Fgettyimages-2159963732.jpg 1600w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/5568x3132+0+290/resize/1800/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F04%2F09%2F0cc743054c958358ca31a45e2fd8%2Fgettyimages-2159963732.jpg 1800w" data-template="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/5568x3132+0+290/resize/{width}/quality/{quality}/format/{format}/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F04%2F09%2F0cc743054c958358ca31a45e2fd8%2Fgettyimages-2159963732.jpg" sizes="(min-width: 1025px) 650px, calc(100vw - 30px)" class="img" type="image/webp" /&gt;             &lt;source srcset="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/5568x3132+0+290/resize/400/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F04%2F09%2F0cc743054c958358ca31a45e2fd8%2Fgettyimages-2159963732.jpg 400w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/5568x3132+0+290/resize/600/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F04%2F09%2F0cc743054c958358ca31a45e2fd8%2Fgettyimages-2159963732.jpg 600w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/5568x3132+0+290/resize/800/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F04%2F09%2F0cc743054c958358ca31a45e2fd8%2Fgettyimages-2159963732.jpg 800w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/5568x3132+0+290/resize/900/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F04%2F09%2F0cc743054c958358ca31a45e2fd8%2Fgettyimages-2159963732.jpg 900w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/5568x3132+0+290/resize/1200/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F04%2F09%2F0cc743054c958358ca31a45e2fd8%2Fgettyimages-2159963732.jpg 1200w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/5568x3132+0+290/resize/1600/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F04%2F09%2F0cc743054c958358ca31a45e2fd8%2Fgettyimages-2159963732.jpg 1600w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/5568x3132+0+290/resize/1800/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F04%2F09%2F0cc743054c958358ca31a45e2fd8%2Fgettyimages-2159963732.jpg 1800w" data-template="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/5568x3132+0+290/resize/{width}/quality/{quality}/format/{format}/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F04%2F09%2F0cc743054c958358ca31a45e2fd8%2Fgettyimages-2159963732.jpg" sizes="(min-width: 1025px) 650px, calc(100vw - 30px)" class="img" type="image/jpeg" /&gt;             &lt;img src="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/5568x3132+0+290/resize/1100/quality/50/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F04%2F09%2F0cc743054c958358ca31a45e2fd8%2Fgettyimages-2159963732.jpg" data-template="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/5568x3132+0+290/resize/{width}/quality/{quality}/format/{format}/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F04%2F09%2F0cc743054c958358ca31a45e2fd8%2Fgettyimages-2159963732.jpg" class="img" alt="Dogs might enjoy participating in daytime activities for July 4th — like this dog named Charlie, decked out for a parade in Salisbury, Mass., in 2024. But when fireworks start, veterinarians say it&amp;#039;s time to keep pets inside and away from loud startling noises." loading="lazy" /&gt;         &lt;/picture&gt; &lt;/div&gt; &lt;div class="credit-caption"&gt;     &lt;div class="caption-wrap"&gt;         &lt;div class="caption" aria-label="Image caption"&gt;             &lt;p&gt;                 Dogs might enjoy participating in daytime activities for July 4th — like this dog named Charlie, decked out for a parade in Salisbury, Mass., in 2024. But when fireworks start, veterinarians say it's time to keep pets inside and away from loud startling noises.                 &lt;b class="credit" aria-label="Image credit"&gt;                                          Joseph Prezioso/AFP via Getty Images                                      &lt;/b&gt;                 &lt;b class="hide-caption"&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;             &lt;/p&gt;         &lt;/div&gt;               &lt;b class="toggle-caption"&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;     &lt;/div&gt;       &lt;/div&gt;    &lt;/div&gt;    &lt;p&gt;The July Fourth fireworks are expected to be larger than ever this year, not just in the U.S. capital but across the country as part of the celebration for America's 250th birthday. Dr. Michael Bailey, president of the American Veterinary Medical Association, says that dogs and cats can hear and feel fireworks from four times farther away than humans can. Here are some tips for pet owners to help their animals &lt;a href="https://www.npr.org/2026/06/28/g-s1-130446/fireworks-pets-dogs-cats" target="_blank"&gt;cope with the loud explosions&lt;/a&gt; and bright flashes.&lt;br&gt;&lt;/p&gt;       &lt;ul class="edTag"&gt;&lt;li&gt;🐕 Get your pet outside for some exercise on a day you know there will be fireworks later so that when they do happen, your pet will be ready to sleep.&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;🐕 Create a safe, calm environment in your home, ideally in a central area away from exterior walls, to provide pets with a buffer against loud noises and bright flashes. You can also offer them a toy and play the TV or radio to help soothe them.&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;🐕 If you need to walk your dog or cat after dark, be sure to use a leash and ensure they have updated ID tags and microchips.&lt;/li&gt;&lt;/ul&gt;   &lt;h3 class="edTag"&gt;3 things to know before you go&lt;/h3&gt;   &lt;div id="resg-s1-131100" class="bucketwrap image large"&gt;             &lt;div     class="imagewrap has-source-dimensions"     data-crop-type=""     style="         --source-width: 2121;         --source-height: 1193;     " &gt;         &lt;picture&gt;             &lt;source srcset="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/2121x1193+0+221/resize/400/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F2d%2Fc7%2F929e0d1f48fa839227c613eeaaa8%2Fgettyimages-2278801668.jpg 400w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/2121x1193+0+221/resize/600/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F2d%2Fc7%2F929e0d1f48fa839227c613eeaaa8%2Fgettyimages-2278801668.jpg 600w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/2121x1193+0+221/resize/800/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F2d%2Fc7%2F929e0d1f48fa839227c613eeaaa8%2Fgettyimages-2278801668.jpg 800w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/2121x1193+0+221/resize/900/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F2d%2Fc7%2F929e0d1f48fa839227c613eeaaa8%2Fgettyimages-2278801668.jpg 900w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/2121x1193+0+221/resize/1200/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F2d%2Fc7%2F929e0d1f48fa839227c613eeaaa8%2Fgettyimages-2278801668.jpg 1200w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/2121x1193+0+221/resize/1600/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F2d%2Fc7%2F929e0d1f48fa839227c613eeaaa8%2Fgettyimages-2278801668.jpg 1600w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/2121x1193+0+221/resize/1800/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F2d%2Fc7%2F929e0d1f48fa839227c613eeaaa8%2Fgettyimages-2278801668.jpg 1800w" d